name: Penicillamine
Reason: Penicillamine has several functional groups that affect its melting point. Starting with the backbone of the molecule, the aliphatic carbon chain tends to have a relatively low melting point. However, substituents on this chain significantly modify this property. The carboxylic acid (-COOH) group generally increases the melting point due to the potential for hydrogen bonding and stronger dipole interactions which can be estimated as +50. The thiol (-SH) group typically raises the melting point as well because of its propensity to form intermolecular interactions; it's less polar than an OH group so let's estimate less of an increase, say +20. The presence of an amine (-NH2) group also increases the melting point through hydrogen bonding, so we might add another +30 for this group. Lastly, there is a tertiary carbon (C(C)(C)S) which may slightly decrease the melting point because of the methyl groups that tend to lower the ability to pack efficiently, so we might deduct around -5 for this. If we consider a simple aliphatic amine as a baseline with a melting point around 50, adding these estimated values gives us a predicted melting point.
